<font color="#FF0000">MEMORIES</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jun 11 19:28:50 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I saw this site profiled on channel 5 in Boston. I was surprised that so many other people have the same feelings about the war<br>
as I did. I joined the Navy in 1968, just before I turned 18 1/2, the magic age in which you were eligible to become cannon fodder.<br>
I figured that if I joined the Navy that I wouldn't go to 'Nam. Silly me! I was stationed on the U.S.S. Parsons (DDG-33) as a Boilerman.(yesterday<br>
I couldn't spell BT, And today I are one.)The captain of the ship didn't let the crew in on much of what was going on in our part of world.<br>
I didn't even know about Kent State until I got back home a year later. I remember coming home after being away for 2 years and racing through SF airport, with cane in hand<br>
and my newly pressed dress blues on my back. The first round eyed girl I had seen in two years came over to me, called me a baby killer and spat in my face. I had no<br>
idea what the hell she was talking about. That still bothers me to this day. <br>
When Desert Storm broke out, I tried to volunteer so's I could redeem myself in my mine by fighting in a &quot;rightious war&quot;<br>
I've told my son that if there were a draft, that I would personally pack his bags and drive him to the Canadian border, kiss him goodby and tell<br>
him to stay there until this country makes good on there promise to back their fighting forces. So far, the government has not done this. Statisics show that the<br>
largest group of homeless people are veterans. Pitiful!!<br>
Bob Pratt 
